Fresh-eyes pass done on `src/blog/people/drafts/Olivia-Cooke.md`. Notes are appended in a `FRESH EYES REVIEW` block at the bottom (no prior block existed, so nothing was stacked). I made no body edits.

**The two biggest issues I flagged:**

1. **The role table cheats on its own thesis.** The piece argues Cooke "keeps picking the same woman — someone braced against a collapse," but her most-seen film, *Ready Player One* (Art3mis), is missing entirely, and Art3mis is a confident rebel, not a fraying woman. Any reader who knows her filmography lands on it instantly and feels the pattern was cherry-picked. It's salvageable — Art3mis hides her real face because she thinks her birthmark makes her unlovable, which is the same "I'll be found out" wound — but right now the strongest counter to the central claim goes unaddressed.

2. **The growth arc has no engine.** "What Olivia Cooke wants now" credits her new calm to nothing concrete, but she herself credits therapy and a stable relationship (Ralph Davis; "only this year have I been able to say: Olivia, just rest"). That evidences the Type-9-in-growth claim the rabbit hole currently just asserts.

Also flagged: her actual breakout, *Me and Earl and the Dying Girl*, is absent despite reinforcing the table's "a body that could fail" note; some recycling of "torture from within" / "so vain, so shallow" across three sections; and I preserved-noted what's working (the Alicent open→close callback, the café-firing interior beat, the Instagram empathy turn).

Sources for the reality check: [Variety — RPO casting](https://variety.com/2015/film/news/olivia-cooke-ready-player-one-steve-spielberg-1201591266/), [MovieWeb — Me and Earl](https://movieweb.com/the-girlfriend-olivia-cooke-me-and-earl-and-the-dying-girl/), [Hollywood Reporter interview](https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-features/olivia-cooke-interview-the-girlfriend-house-of-the-dragon-1236352849/), [Forbes 2025 interview](https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffconway/2025/09/09/the-girlfriend-star-olivia-cooke-on-her-career-fame-and-normal-life/).
